{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d09c59b3-ed70-4bb0-bf14-fe5960e7126a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sequence Types"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "6ace3ca1-1afe-489f-bac1-418d2aa2fb0f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "What is a sequence?\n",
    "\n",
    "In math: S = x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4, .... (countable sequence)\n",
    "Note that sequence of indices: 1, 2, 3, 4, ...\n",
    "Refer to any item in sequence using index number x_2 or S[2]\n",
    "Have a concept of a first element, second element and so on -> positional ordering\n",
    "Python lists have a concept of positional ordering but sets do not\n",
    "A list is a sequence type, a set is not\n",
    "In Python we start index numbers at 0 and not 1 (we will see why later)\n",
    "\n",
    "S = x_0, x_1, x_2, x_3, .... -> S[2] is the third element"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "c83c9e3c-4de8-45ad-8ed7-9f055c0b0aa2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Built-In Sequence Types\n",
    "\n",
    "mutable: lists, bytearrays\n",
    "immutable: strings, tuples, range, bytes\n",
    "\n",
    "We have seen that a tuple is more than just a sequence type, it is a data structure\n",
    "Range is more limited than lists, strings, and tuples\n",
    "\n",
    "Additional Standard Types: \n",
    "(collections package) namedtuple, deque\n",
    "(array module) array"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "dbb2fcc2-daa4-4a76-b965-068e28456044",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Homogenous vs Heterogenous Sequences\n",
    "\n",
    "Strings are homogenous sequences; each element is of the same type (a character) 'python'\n",
    "Lists are heterogenous sequences; each element may be a different type [1, 10.5, 'python']\n",
    "\n",
    "Homogenous sequences are usually more efficient (storage wise)\n",
    "e.g. prefer using string of characters rather than a list or tuple of characters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "d81fb399-a1ad-4f84-8da6-5f33f1f3f301",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterable Type vs Sequence Type\n",
    "\n",
    "What does it mean for an object to be iterable?\n",
    "Containter type of object and we can list out elements in object one by one\n",
    "\n",
    "So any sequence type is iterable\n",
    "l = [1, 2, 3] for e in l; l[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "But an iterable is not necessarily a sequence type -> iterables are more general\n",
    "s = {1, 2, 3} for e in s; s[0] XXXX NO ORDERING"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "462598c0-7d5e-424f-b683-4083da19556f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Standard Sequence Methods\n",
    "\n",
    "Built-in sequence types, both mutable and immutable, support the following methods:\n",
    "x in s\n",
    "x not in s\n",
    "s1 + s2 (concatenation)\n",
    "s * n (or n * s) where n is an integer (repetition)\n",
    "len(s)\n",
    "min(s) / max(s) only works if ordering between elements of s is defined (not the same as ordering position)\n",
    "s.index(x) index of first occurrence of x in s\n",
    "s.index(x, i) index of first occurence of x in s at/after index i\n",
    "s.index(x, i, j) index of first occurence of x in s at/after index i and before index j\n",
    "s[i] the element at index i\n",
    "s[i:j] the slice from index i to (but not including) j\n",
    "s[i:j:k] extended slice from index i, to (but not including) j, in steps of k\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that slices will not return the same container type (come back for more detail)\n",
    "Range objects are more restrictive; no concatentation/repetition; min, max, in, not in are not as efficient"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "9fd2135b-d0b5-431a-afdf-ca1ab1b54350",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Hashing\n",
    "\n",
    "Immutable sequence types may support hashing hash(s) but not if they contain mutable types"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f6cae70e-0ace-49cf-a7a1-9ebf9365fafa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Review: Beware of Concatenations\n",
    "\n",
    "x = [1, 2]\n",
    "a = x + x\n",
    "a -> [1, 2, 1, 2]\n",
    "\n",
    "x = 'python'\n",
    "a = x + x\n",
    "a -> 'pythonpython'\n",
    "\n",
    "x = [[0, 0]]\n",
    "a = x + x\n",
    "a -> [[0, 0], [0, 0]]\n",
    "\n",
    "id(x[0]) == id(a[0]) == id(a[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "a[0] is x[0]\n",
    "a[1] is x[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "a[0][0] = 100\n",
    "a -> [[100, 0], [100, 0]]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "ed9cd6e3-5008-4378-b6ab-51c5ad9e162b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Review: Beware of Repetitions\n",
    "\n",
    "a = [1, 2] * 2\n",
    "a -> [1, 2, 1, 2]\n",
    "\n",
    "a = 'python' * 2\n",
    "a -> 'pythonpython'\n",
    "\n",
    "a = [[0, 0]] *2\n",
    "a -> [[0, 0], [0, 0]]\n",
    "\n",
    "id([0, 0]) == id(a[0]) == id(a[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "a[0, 0] = 100\n",
    "\n",
    "a -> [[100, 0], [100, 0]]\n",
    "\n",
    "Same happens here but because strings are immutable it's quite safe\n",
    "a = ['python'] * 2\n",
    "a -> ['python', 'python']\n",
    "...can't change python anyways"
   ]
  },
